cannot readily adapt to sudden pressure increases","Pulmonary vascular resistance decreases","Ventilation-perfusion matching improves","Left ventricular preload typically increases"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn acute pulmonary embolism:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeep vein thrombosis of the upper limb\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most common source -the correct answer would be DVT of the lower limbs. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eright ventricle cannot readily adapt to sudden pressure increases\u003C/strong\u003E - this is true, as it is thin-walled and designed for low pressure circulation (mean pressures in the pulmonary circuit are ~15mmHg compared to ~90mmHg in the systemic system). \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary vascular resistance\u003C/strong\u003E increases due to mechanical obstruction and hypoxic vasoconstriction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentilation-perfusion matching\u003C/strong\u003E worsens due to areas of lung being ventilated but not perfused (dead space)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft ventricular preload\u003C/strong\u003E decreases due to reduced right ventricular output\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe acute rise in pulmonary vascular resistance and pressures leads to right ventricular strain and potential failure, as the right ventricle is not designed to pump against high resistance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute pulmonary embolism most commonly originates from deep vein thrombosis in the proximal leg veins above the knee","The right ventricle has limited capacity to generate pressure against acute increases in pulmonary vascular resistance","Ventilation-perfusion mismatch in pulmonary embolism leads to increased dead space ventilation"],"references":["Doherty S. Pulmonary embolism An update. Aust Fam Physician. 2017 Nov;46(11):816-820. PMID: 29101916.","Shah IK, Merfeld JM, Chun J, Tak T. Pathophysiology and Management of Pulmonary Embolism. Int J Angiol. 2022 Sep 23;31(3):143-149. doi: 10.1055/s-0042-1756204. PMID: 36157092; PMCID: PMC9507564.","Mason, R. J., Broaddus, V. C., Martin, T. R., King, T. E., Schraufnagel, D., Murray, J. F., \u0026 Nadel, J. A. (2010). Murray and Nadel\u0027s textbook of respiratory medicine E-book: 2-volume set. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51328"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15482"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51328"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T12:17:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T12:17:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8173"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65883"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://a